I’m skeptical that minor changes in the status quo will to deliver the sustainable, equitable fisheries that people are striving for. Kudos to those that are starting to think this through. I’m just worried we are moving fast enough. Climate change is not going to wait for us.

Our current system largely maximizes the amount we catch of a few species. That rests on judgments of what we consider a healthy ecosystem, and what we consider a functional fishing community. We may need to re-examine all of those relationships.
But that doesn’t address the underpining ethical, moral and economic decisions that created those frameworks, or their dependence on a wild ecosystem behaving within an understood level of variance.

In fisheries, we are absolutely not grappling with the fact that we have, at minimum, thirty years of increasingly severe and frequent impacts ahead. Most fishery mgmt is business-as-usual, trusting that our existing frameworks will be okay if we just put the right science in.

Human #health impacts: Climate change can have a range of impacts on human health, including heat-related illness, respiratory problems due to air #pollution, and the spread of diseases carried by ticks and mosquitoes.
Changes in wildlife behavior and #habitat: Climate change can lead to changes in the distribution and behavior of wildlife, as well as the loss of habitat due to rising sea levels and other impacts.
Changes in growing seasons: As the climate changes, the timing of growing seasons is shifting, which is affecting the availability and quality of #food.

Changes in precipitation patterns: Some areas may experience more extreme precipitation, such as heavy rain or snow, as the climate changes. Other areas may experience less precipitation, leading to drought.
#Wildfires: Warmer temperatures and drought can lead to an increase in wildfires, which can have serious impacts on air quality, #wildlife, and #human communities.
#Drought: As the planet warms, some areas may experience more drought, as higher temperatures lead to increased #evaporation and reduced #precipitation.
More frequent and intense storms: As the Earth's atmosphere warms, it can hold more moisture, leading to more frequent and intense storms, such as #hurricanes and #typhoons.

More frequent and intense #heatwaves: Heatwaves are becoming more frequent and more intense as the planet warms. This can lead to heat exhaustion and other health problems, as well as crop failures and wildfires.
Rising #sea levels: As the #Earth's temperature increases, polar ice caps and #glaciers are melting, causing sea levels to rise. This can lead to #flooding and coastal erosion in some areas.

Increasing #global temperatures: Earth's average surface #temperature has risen about 1.8 degrees Fahrenheit (1 degree Celsius) since the late 19th century, largely due to the increase in #carbondioxide and other heat-trapping gases in the #atmosphere.

5/5 Yes, it sucks, because we are right, but when people have the freedom to choose in a complex situation, they often start asking better questions and sometimes start challenging their own points of view. Might be better than digging ever deeper trenches between us and them.

4/5 (This is true for us, as well, that’s why we get so upset with certain people.) What can we do? As much as it might go against what we hold dear, we need to start presenting issues as complex, not simple. And then allow them the freedom to choose.

3/5 We are right, they are wrong. No doubt about it. But as soon as we position an issue as a right/wrong binary choice, people tend to dig in and defend their beliefs.As soon as they are accused of being in the wrong, their position becomes an emotional one, not a rational one.

2/5 I think it is time to take responsibility for the fact that those of us who want to convince “the other side” about the error of their ways are part of the problem. Not because of our intentions, but because of how we frame our arguments.
